{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6fb588d8-7330-483c-8284-be8305dcf926","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- The Android handlers receive the `Activity`; iOS handlers receive the `UIApplication`.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n\nThis lets you run cross-platform or platform-specific logic at the exact native lifecycle moment without subclassing platform classes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9f694604-6e45-4a71-8a5a-3d29c46d4e8b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":325,"requestId":"0813:187D22:A1F2E6:BBD999:69F2A879"},"id":"c2cbed78-184c-4a23-bebf-f9b35e90b7e2","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:55:28.272Z","parentId":"554491f5-b4d4-4597-9d72-2bac8b52f36a"}
